  <description type="1">
   <narrative xml:lang="EN">COOPAMAK is one of the 5 cooperatives participating in the Ruzizi Rice Project 18at-8092.
The Mashaka Agricultural Cooperative of Kilomonyi  COOPAMAK  exists in its present form since 2014. But its history goes back more or less thirty years.
  
In fact  it is in 1982 that seven agricultural producers of the village of Kilomonyi  constitute a peasant organization with the aim of mobilizing the village community to free a part of the terroir imprisoned in the marsh and covered bushes (mashaka in Swahili) in the Ruzizi River Delta. In 1993  the peasant organization was structured and adopted a specific name: Microproject food rice Mashaka Kilomonyi (MIPROVIRIMA). It formalized the membership of 176 members and provided a staff composed of a director  an agronomist and a secretary. With this technical support  the members traced the irrigation channels and ensured its regular cleaning. In 2010  MIPROVIRIMA joined the Ruzizi Agricultural Producers Cooperative (COPA-Ruzizi) as a Farmers&apos; Group with headquarters in Uvira. In 2014  members of MIPROVIRIMA left COPA-Ruzizi to found an autonomous cooperative  the current COOPAMAK. Main activities done are storage and dehulling of paddy  as well as the joint selling of rice. COOPAMAK was informed of the mission of Agriterra and that it made contact. She hopes to receive technical and financial support to rehabilitate her dehuller and access more profitable markets.</narrative>
  </description>
  <description type="2">
   <narrative xml:lang="EN">The cooperative would like to  professionalize in the activity of collecting and selling rice of its members  in order to make it more profitable. So  they can earn more income and sell large quantities of quality rice to the Bralima.</narrative>
  </description>
